Preheat your oven to 200°C. Lightly oil a large #baking tray{} (use 2 trays if
you're cooking for 3 or 4 people). Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2 cm chunks
(no need to peel). Trim the ends from the @carrot{2}(ends trimmed, no need to
peel) and chop into 1cm thick rounds. Halve, peel and chop the
@red onion{1}(peeled and chopped into wedges) into wedges (3 per half).

Pop all the veggies onto your tray(s), season with @salt{} and @ground black
pepper{}, add a drizzle of @oil{} and sprinkle on the @dried thyme{1/2%tsp}.
Use your hands to rub the flavourings all over the veggies and arrange in one
even layer.

Nestle the @British Honey Mustard Sausages{4} among the veggies and bake until
the veggies are soft and golden and the sausages are cooked through,
~{25-30%minutes}. Turn everything halfway through cooking to make sure it all
browns evenly.

> IMPORTANT: The sausages are cooked when they are no longer pink in the
> middle.

Meanwhile, heat a #frying pan{} over high heat (no oil). While it heats up,
trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed) and cut into 1cm thick rounds. Pop into the
#frying pan{} in one layer and dry-fry for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side.

> TIP: You want the courgettes to char so don't overcrowd the pan! Once ready,
> transfer to a #plate{}; we will reheat them later.

Allow the pan to cool before moving on to making the gravy.

Pour the @water{200%ml} into the frying pan you used for the courgette and
add the @onion marmalade{40%g}. Bring to the boil on medium heat then stir in
and dissolve the @chicken stock powder{1/2%tsp}. Simmer, stirring occasionally,
until the gravy has thickened and reduced by a third, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Two mins before you're ready to serve, reheat the courgette by adding to the
tray(s) in the oven. When everything is ready, share the roasted veggies
between your plates and top with the sausages. Spoon the onion gravy all
over. Tuck in.